Michael,

Cantera flags some reactions as duplicatess that Chemkin does not.  All 
you have to do is tell Cantera that you intend this by adding:

options = &quot;duplicate&quot;

for each reaction it flags as an undeclared duplicate, for example:

falloff_reaction( &quot;h + o2 (+ M) &lt;=&gt; ho2 (+ M)&quot;
          kf = [4.52000E+013, 0, 0],
          kf0   = [1.05000E+019, -1.257, 0],
          efficiencies = &quot; ch4:10  co:1.9  co2:3.8  h2:0  h2o:0  n2:0 &quot;,
          options = &quot;duplicate&quot;)

This is done intentionallly, since a reaction like h + o2 (+ n2) &lt;=&gt; 
ho2 (+ n2) could also be written as h + o2 (+ M) &lt;=&gt; ho2 (+ M) with all 
efficiencies set to zero except the one for n2.
Also, if you have two reactions
  A + B &lt;=&gt; C + D
and
C + D &lt;=&gt; A + B
Cantera says these are duplicates, but Chemkin does not.
Cantera performs some other checks too, such as whether NASA polynomial 
thermo parameterizations are continuous at the midpoint temperature, 
etc.

These extra checks can help find error in reaction mechanisms that 
might otherwise go unnoticed, which is especially a problem with very 
large mechanisms.

Dave


